ttle, just refer to the earlier theory\\n- You may ignore this box if your theories have not changed at all\",\"I think that Nathan attacked his father, whether intending to kill him or not, likely because of a disagreement about inheritance. Nathan's business seems sketchy, and he might need the inheritance more than he lets on. This would also explain the mess of papers if someone was looking for something in them. Nathan says the door was locked, but Melissa says it wouldn't have been because of the fire making the room too warm. This lines up with the ashes in the fireplace suggesting it was used last night. If the door was unlocked Nathan could have simply entered. His alibi with the work call is convincing, but he could have used the shouting to cover the sound of an attack. Melissa is out of the running because she couldn't physically attack Victor, even though her motives seem very strong. Frances has an argument with her uncle, but not one that seems worthy of murder, and there is no evidence to suggest that Francis entered the room from outside. 80%\",\"Not very. I focussed in on the human factor and didn't consider that it really was an accident. I considered the dog being the one in the room, but dismissed it because the dog would not have murderous intent. I rushed over details that had I lined them up properly would have created a different picture. I got some things right about the family, but missed the obvious.\"][\" \",\"\",\"\",\"the first thing I would check is the body, examine for other injuries etc, see if anything seems missing\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"mud indicates outside, where did it come from?\",\"How did the attacker (if an attacker) enter the room?\",\"\",\"Is there any reason to what was smashed? any clues?\",\"\",\"is there anything noteworthy near the fireplace/on the mantle that would have been an object of interest?\",\"\",\"Some things indicate victor was going to bed, darkness could also hide an attacker. Thoroughness\",\"\",\"\"